      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "feat(fs): allow configured workspace aliases",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nWhat problem does this PR solve?\n\n- `tools.fs.workspaceOnly=true` currently rejects workspace symlink parents whose realpath lands outside the agent workspace. That blocks memory flushes for setups where `memory/` is intentionally shared outside the per-agent workspace.\n\nWhy does this matter now?\n\n- Issue #90977 captures a real deployed layout where `memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md` cannot be written because `memory` is a workspace symlink to a shared memory directory.\n- Disabling `workspaceOnly` or broadening the entire workspace would fix the symptom but weakens the filesystem boundary more than needed.\n\nWhat is the intended outcome?\n\n- Add `tools.fs.workspaceAliases` as an explicit, exact alias allowlist for `tools.fs.workspaceOnly=true`.\n- Allow read/write/edit and memory-flush append-only writes through the configured in-workspace alias path.\n- Keep direct target paths rejected and keep default symlink escape rejection unchanged when no alias is configured.\n\nWhat is intentionally out of scope?\n\n- No change to default filesystem behavior.\n- No broad allowed-roots model for all file tools.\n- No `apply_patch` alias support in this PR.\n- No migration or automatic alias discovery.\n\nWhat does success look like?\n\n- Operators can configure a narrow alias such as `path: \"memory\"` and `target: \"/.../workspace/memory\"` while keeping `workspaceOnly` enabled.\n- The alias path must realpath exactly to the configured target root before file tools can use it.\n- A model still cannot write to the target directory by addressing the target path directly.\n\nWhat should reviewers focus on?\n\n- Whether `workspaceAliases` is the right config shape and location under `tools.fs`.\n- Whether the exact-realpath check and direct-target rejection preserve the intended security boundary.\n- Whether applying the alias to memory-flush append-only writes, read, write, and edit is the right scope.\n\n## Linked context\n\nWhich issue does this close?\n\nCloses #90977\n\nWhich issues, PRs, or discussions are related?\n\nRelated #38622\nRelated #7722\nRelated #85876\n\nWas this requested by a maintainer or owner?\n\n- No maintainer explicitly requested this implementation. ClawSweeper kept #90977 open and flagged it for maintainer/product/security review, with a narrow exact-realpath alias called out as the likely fix shape.\n\n## Real behavior proof (required for external PRs)\n\n- Behavior or issue addressed: `openclaw.write`/memory flush can append to `memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md` when `memory` is a configured workspace alias symlinked outside the agent workspace, without disabling `tools.fs.workspaceOnly`.\n- Real environment tested: Local Linux checkout of this PR at `7c865a65e0fc413e69f73bbefda1bbfbcd75748c`, using the actual `createOpenClawCodingTools` runtime path against real temporary filesystem directories and symlinks.\n- Exact steps or command run after this patch: `./node_modules/.bin/tsx` inline proof script that imported `createOpenClawCodingTools`, configured `tools.fs.workspaceOnly=true` plus `tools.fs.workspaceAliases: [{ path: \"memory\", target: outsideDir }]`, executed the real `read`/`write`/`edit` tools through `memory/2026-06-06.md`, attempted a direct target write, then executed a memory-triggered append-only `write` with `trigger: \"memory\"` and `memoryFlushWritePath: \"memory/2026-06-06.md\"`.\n- Evidence after fix (screenshot, recording, terminal capture, console output, redacted runtime log, linked artifact, or copied live output):\n\n```text\nPR #90986 live file-tool proof on local Linux checkout\nhead: 7c865a65e0fc413e69f73bbefda1bbfbcd75748c\nworkspace: <tmp-openclaw-ws-alias-proof>/workspace\nalias path: memory -> <tmp-openclaw-ws-alias-proof>/memory-target\nconfigured target: <tmp-openclaw-ws-alias-proof>/memory-target\nalias realpath matches configured target: true\nalias write result: Successfully wrote 12 bytes to memory/2026-06-06.md\nalias read contains seed memory: true\ndirect target write rejected: yes: Path escapes sandbox root (<tmp-openclaw-ws-alias-proof>/workspace): <tmp-openclaw-ws-alias-proof>/memory-target/2026-06-06.md. Use a relative path under `.openclaw/tmp/` inside the workspace for scratch/temp/meta files that file tools need to read or write later.\nmemory flush append result: Appended content to memory/2026-06-06.md.\nfinal target content after append:\n  edited memory\n  flush note\n```\n\n- Observed result after fix: Alias path file-tool write/read/edit succeeded through `memory/2026-06-06.md`; the alias symlink realpath exactly matched the configured target; direct writes to the outside target path still rejected; memory-triggered append-only write appended through the alias path.\n- What was not tested: Full `pnpm check`/broad CI and a live deployed Gateway process. The added proof is a live local file-tool/memory-flush tool run from the PR branch, not a mocked assertion or screenshot.\n- Proof limitations or environment constraints: Temporary filesystem paths are redacted in the terminal capture. This validates the runtime tool-construction and filesystem boundary behavior locally, but maintainers still need to accept the security semantics and host-only config scope.\n- Before evidence (optional but encouraged): Existing coverage already showed outside-workspace symlink parents reject under `workspaceOnly`; #90977 includes the observed deployed failure message: `openclaw.write` rejected `memory/2026-06-06.md` with `path alias escape blocked`.\n\n## Tests and validation\n\nWhich commands did you run?\n\n- `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs src/agents/agent-tools.workspace-paths.test.ts src/agents/agent-tools.workspace-only-false.test.ts src/agents/tool-fs-policy.test.ts src/config/config.schema-regressions.test.ts`\n- `git diff --check`\n\nWhat regression coverage was added or updated?\n\n- Added config schema coverage for global and agent-level `tools.fs.workspaceAliases`.\n- Added tool policy coverage for global alias inheritance and agent alias override.\n- Added filesystem behavior coverage for configured outside-workspace symlink aliases, direct target rejection, and memory-triggered append-only writes through the alias.\n\nWhat failed before this fix, if known?\n\n- The deployed repro in #90977 failed memory flush writes because `memory/2026-06-06.md` resolved outside the agent workspace through a symlink.\n- Existing tests already asserted that outside-workspace symlink parents are rejected under `workspaceOnly`; this PR keeps that default and adds an explicit configured alias path.\n\nIf no test was added, why not?\n\n- Tests were added.\n\n## Risk checklist\n\nDid user-visible behavior change? (`Yes/No`)\n\nYes. Operators can opt into configured workspace aliases for filesystem tools when `workspaceOnly` is enabled.\n\nDid config, environment, or migration behavior change? (`Yes/No`)\n\nYes. This adds `tools.fs.workspaceAliases` to the config schema/types/help/labels/tags and docs. There is no migration because the default remains unchanged.\n\nDid security, auth, secrets, network, or tool execution behavior change? (`Yes/No`)\n\nYes. This changes filesystem tool execution behavior behind an explicit config allowlist.\n\nWhat is the highest-risk area?\n\n- The new config widens the effective workspace boundary for file tools if an operator configures an alias incorrectly.\n\nHow is that risk mitigated?\n\n- Aliases are disabled by default.\n- Alias `path` must be relative to the workspace.\n- Alias `target` must be an absolute existing directory.\n- The workspace alias path must realpath exactly to the configured target root.\n- File tools must address files through the alias path; direct target paths still reject.\n- Existing default outside-workspace symlink rejection remains covered.\n\n## Current review state\n\nWhat is the next action?\n\n- Maintainer/product/security review of the config shape and boundary semantics.\n\nWhat is still waiting on author, maintainer, CI, or external proof?\n\n- Waiting on CI and maintainer product/security review.\n- Added ClawSweeper-requested local live file-tool proof for alias success, direct-target rejection, and memory-triggered append-only write behavior. Full `pnpm check` or deployed Gateway proof can still be run if maintainers want it before merge.\n\nWhich bot or reviewer comments were addressed?\n\n- This PR follows ClawSweeper's issue guidance from #90977 by implementing a narrow exact-realpath alias policy instead of disabling `workspaceOnly` or broadening the whole workspace.\n",
